 mentally ill, non-whites, and others. Ultimately, Craig argues, the debates that began in these early political and literary texts—texts that document both the birth control movement’s idealism and its exclusionary rhetoric—helped shape the complex legacy of family planning and women’s rights with which the United States and the United Kingdom still struggle.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aBirth control in literature. 0aBirth controlxSocial aspectszGreat Britain. 0aBirth controlxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aEnglish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEugenics in literature. 0aFeminism and literature. 0aWomen and literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081356212440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813562124423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813562124/original  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK